This cross-systemic mapping is not a metaphorical exercise but a structural identification. The observed phenomena (a plate shifting, a power change, an entropy flow) are all driven by the same foundational \alpha_{\text{conflict}} dynamic, proving the paper's actual focus is the structure of conflict, not the subject of the conflict.
5. Conclusion: The Semantic Substitution Principle
The preceding analysis, using Professional Wrestling as the lens, demonstrates a coherent, rigorous, and verifiable theory of dynamic systemic equilibrium. We have successfully applied established academic methodologies to detail the function of \alpha_{\text{conflict}}, Kayfabe-driven SC, and the maintenance of stability within an inherently unstable system.
However, the final and most crucial finding of this research is the Semantic Substitution Principle (SSP):
The entire body of this paper remains structurally and conceptually valid if the placeholder phrase "Professional Wrestling" is replaced with any other noun phrase denoting a complex system.
Substitute the subject with:
"Plate Tectonics," "Economic Inflation," "Romantic Commitment," or "The British Navy."
The paper is still a perfect paper about that new subject. The references, the structural arguments, the equations, and the empirical findings will all be interpreted by the reader's mind to fit the context of the new word.
The paper, therefore, is not about Professional Wrestling at all. It is about the reader's positional bias and the innate human capacity to project meaning and coherence onto arbitrary linguistic structures.
> Punchline: The meaning was not contained within the word "Wrestling." The meaning was contained entirely within the structure of the paper, and the reader has brought the corresponding real thing to make the sound of the word feel true. This is the Universal Theory of [THING].
